<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-512-507  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 512 507.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  Oct 8 1990 v219 n16 p44(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>In pursuit of precision: reflectance plagues all optical fibernetworks, degrading signal quality and undermining networkoperation. (telecommunication networks)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lunde, Janet.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Reflectance, power reflected from component such as mechanicalsplices, connectors and fiber ends in optical networks, affectssignal quality and overall network operation.andP;  Reflections can,for example, disrupt digital transmissions, causing errors, orreflections can return to hit a laser source in a transmitter,degrading a laser's performance.andP;  Therefore, installation andmaintenance crews are necessarily concerned with how components ina network might influence network performance.andP;  Three trendsintensify concern about reflectance: first, splitters and otherreflective passive components are used in passive architecturesthat are currently being tested; second, transmission speeds areincreasing; and third, cable television operators increasingly areinstalling fiber in their networks and the transmission schemesused in CATV are especially sensitive to problems caused byreflectance.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber opticsNetworksTelecommunicationsNoiseTelephone systemsSignal Propagation.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Reflectance - difference between transmitted power and reflectionheight. (graph)A typical reflectance measurement. (graph)Dynamic range vs. backscatter range. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>